## When to use
Use this skill when you need a detailed view of your Linux system's performance over time. It is particularly useful for identifying bottlenecks, analyzing I/O operations, or understanding CPU and memory utilization patterns.

## Approach
Install the atop command using shell_exec if it is not already available on your system. Use file_read to fetch configuration files or sample data relevant to atop monitoring. Execute atop with specific parameters to focus on particular aspects of resource usage, such as CPU activity (a), disk I/O (d), or network traffic (n). Use ssh_tail to continuously monitor the output of atop in real-time for dynamic system analysis.

## Example
```shell
# Install atop if not installed
shell_exec("apt-get install -y atop")

# Execute atop with focus on CPU and Disk I/O activity, then use ssh_tail to follow the live output.
shell_exec("atop -a -d")
ssh_tail("/var/log/atop/202311.log")  # Assumes log file is stored in this path
```

## Pitfalls
Atop can be resource-intensive itself. Ensure it does not interfere with the performance analysis by running it during off-peak hours or on a less critical system. Additionally, if atop logs are saved to disk, ensure there is sufficient storage space and that the log files do not rotate too frequently which might lead to loss of data.